  "notes": [
    "All transfer applicants must meet the University of California admissions eligibility requirements and the campus’s admission selection criteria. All requirements must be completed by the end of the spring term prior to transfer. For more information on UC admissions eligibility and admission to UC Santa Cruz, visit the Admissions website . The UC Santa Cruz Transfer Admission Guarantee (TAG) is a formal agreement that guarantees your fall admission to your chosen major, provided you are transferring from a California Community College and meet specific requirements. Visit the UC Santa Cruz TAG webpage for more information.",
    "THIS IS A SCREENING MAJOR. Screening majors require completion of specific preparatory coursework and/or a minimum GPA. For details on the specific screening requirements for this major, refer to the \" Transfer Admission Screening Policy \" below. Additional coursework listed under \"Recommended Preparation\" is not required for admission but is strongly recommended to support timely degree completion. For more information, including a list of screening majors and non-screening majors , visit the UCSC Admissions website.",
    "Some Advanced Placement (AP), International Baccalaureate Higher Level (IBH), and Advanced Level (A-level) exams satisfy UCSC course requirements. UCSC's exam credit policies may be found on the Degree Progress Unit website .",
    "Transfer Admission Screening Policy Transfer applicants must complete the articulated equivalents of at least EIGHT of the courses listed in the \"Required Major Preparation Courses\" section below, with a cumulative GPA of 2.8 or better, no later than the end of the spring term prior to starting at UCSC in the fall. All attempted screening courses are included in the cumulative GPA, calculated using UCSC grade point guidelines , even if more than eight screening courses are completed. For community colleges that do not issue “+” or “–” grades, grade points are assigned as follows: A = 4.0, B = 3.0, C = 2.0, D = 1.0. Applicants are strongly encouraged to complete the articulated equivalents of the calculus, general chemistry, and organic chemistry courses listed below. Look for the “Strongly Recommended” notations attached to these courses. Strongly Recommended Major Preparation Although not required for admission, transfer students are strongly encouraged to complete at least TEN courses from \" Required Major Preparation Courses\" if they wish to graduate within two years. Completing organic chemistry before transfer is particularly important. Students may substitute courses from \"Required Major Preparation Courses\" Group 2, sections A or B toward the eight required transfer screening courses for their specific intended major concentration: Section A: Biomolecular Engineering concentration Section B: Bioinformatics concentration Additional Information for Transfer Students are strongly encouraged to prioritize required and recommended major preparation courses and may additionally complete courses that fulfill UC Santa Cruz general education requirements before transferring as time allows. Visit the Baskin Engineering Undergraduate Experience website to learn more about this major. UC Santa Cruz General Catalog: Biomolecular Engineering and Bioinformatics B.S. Program Statement"
